<!--
<!DOCTYPE section SYSTEM "file:/opt/share/xml/Oxygen/docbook/dtd/docbookx.dtd">
--><ns4278:section xmlns:ns4278="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook" xml:id="resources.information.platforms.linux.processControl.whatIsAProcess">

  <ns4279:title xmlns:ns4279="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">What is a process</ns4279:title>
  <ns4280:para xmlns:ns4280="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    A process is one or more threads of execution which run in their own memory space
    (in their own virtual machine). It can be seen as
    <ns4281:itemizedlist xmlns:ns4281="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      <ns4282:listitem xmlns:ns4282="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns4283:para xmlns:ns4283="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        an instance of an executing program together with
      </ns4283:para></ns4282:listitem>
      <ns4284:listitem xmlns:ns4284="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns4285:para xmlns:ns4285="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        the resources required by the program (memory including stack, file handles, ...)  plus
      </ns4285:para></ns4284:listitem>
      <ns4286:listitem xmlns:ns4286="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook"><ns4287:para xmlns:ns4287="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
        the status of execution (CPU registers, the stack frames, ...).
      </ns4287:para></ns4286:listitem>
    </ns4281:itemizedlist>
    Processes transform one or more input streams into one or more output streams.
  </ns4280:para>      
  
  <ns4288:section xmlns:ns4288="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
    <ns4289:title xmlns:ns4289="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">Child processes</ns4289:title>
    <ns4290:para xmlns:ns4290="http://docbook.org/ns/docbook">
      A process can spawn child processes. Child processes do not survive the parent process.  
    </ns4290:para>
  </ns4288:section>
  
</ns4278:section>